<activity xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="act-7-2-1" permid="nza">
  <statement>
    <p permid="oEt">
      Consider the autonomous differential equation
      <me permid="ASL">
        \frac{dy}{dt} = -\frac{1}{2}(y - 4)
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p permid="ULC">
      <ol label="a." permid="UbI">
        <li permid="AiR">
          <p permid="Omw">
            Make a plot of <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> versus <m>y</m> on the axes provided 

            in <xref ref="F-7-2-act-1-2-dydt">Figure</xref>.
            Looking at the graph,
            for what values of <m>y</m> does <m>y</m> increase and for what values of <m>y</m> does <m>y</m> decrease?
          </p>

          <sidebyside widths="50% 44%" margins="0%" valign="bottom" permid="WAP">
            <figure xml:id="F-7-2-act-1-2-dydt" permid="utF">
              <caption>Axes for plotting <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> versus <m>y</m>.</caption>
              <image permid="qtG" source="images/7_2_Act1_1" />
            </figure>

            <figure xml:id="F-7-2-act-1-2" permid="aAO">
              <caption>Axes for plotting the slope field for <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = -\frac 12( y - 4)</m>.</caption>
              <image source="images/7_2_Act1_2" />
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="gqa">
          <p permid="GHX">
            Next, sketch the slope field for this differential equation on the axes provided in <xref ref="F-7-2-act-1-2">Figure</xref>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="Mxj">
          <p permid="mPg">
            Use your work in (b) to sketch
            (on the same axes in <xref ref="F-7-2-act-1-2">Figure</xref>.)
            solutions that satisfy <m>y(0) = 0</m>,
            <m>y(0) = 2</m>, <m>y(0) = 4</m> and <m>y(0) = 6</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="sEs">
          <p permid="SWp">
            Verify that <m>y(t) = 4 + 2e^{-t/2}</m> is a solution to the given differential equation with the initial value <m>y(0) = 6</m>.
            Compare its graph to the one you sketched in (c).
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="YLB">
          <p permid="zdy">
            What is special about the solution where <m>y(0) = 4</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <answer permid="bGh">
    <p permid="Ixk">
      <ol label="a." permid="nUz">
        <li permid="ESK">
          <p permid="fkH">
            When <m>y \lt 4</m>, <m>y</m> is an increasing function of <m>t</m>.
            When <m>y \gt 4</m>, <m>y</m> is a decreasing function of <m>t</m>.
          </p>

          <sidebyside width="50%" permid="CHY">

            <image source="images/7_2_Act1_dydt_plot_soln" permid="FCE">
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="kZT">

          <sidebyside width="50%" permid="iPh">

            <image source="images/7_2_Act1_slope_field_soln" permid="lJN">
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="Rhc">

          <sidebyside width="50%" permid="OWq">

            <image source="images/7_2_Act1_trajectories_soln" permid="RQW">
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="xol">
          <p permid="LrQ">
            <me permid="gZU">
              \frac{dy}{dt} = 2 \left( -\frac{1}{2} e^{-t/2} \right) = -e^{-t/2}
            </me>
            and
            <me permid="Nhd">
              -\frac{1}{2}( y - 4 ) = -\frac{1}{2} \left( 4 + 2e^{-t/2} \right) = -e^{-t/2}
            </me>
            In addition, <m>y(0) = 4 + 2e^0 = 6</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="dvu">
          <p permid="ryZ">
            A constant function.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution permid="vyY">
    <p permid="cqb">
      <ol label="a." permid="HNq">
        <li permid="JCD">
          <p permid="XGi">
            The graph below is a plot of <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> versus <m>y</m>.
            We see that when <m>y \lt 4</m>,
            <m>\frac{dy}{dt} \gt 0</m> and hence <m>y</m> is an increasing function of <m>t</m>.
            We also see that when <m>y \gt 4</m>,
            <m>\frac{dy}{dt} \lt 0</m> and hence <m>y</m> is a decreasing function of <m>t</m>.
          </p>

          <sidebyside width="40%" permid="vdz">

            <image source="images/7_2_Act1_dydt_plot_soln" permid="xYf">
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="pJM">
          <p permid="DNr">
            Next, by sampling points <m>(t,y)</m> in the plane and plotting short lines whose slope is <m>\left. \frac{dy}{dt}\right|_{(t,y)}</m>,
            we create the following slope field for the differential equation <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = -\frac{1}{2}(y - 4)</m>.
          </p>

          <sidebyside width="40%" permid="bkI">

            <image source="images/7_2_Act1_slope_field_soln" permid="efo">
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="VQV">
          <p permid="jUA">
            Finally, by choosing starting points and following the direction of the slope field,
            we generate plots of solutions that satisfy <m>y(0) = 0</m>,
            <m>y(0) = 2</m>, <m>y(0) = 4</m>,
            and <m>y(0) = 6</m>, as shown in the following figure.
          </p>

          <sidebyside width="40%" permid="HrR">

            <image source="images/7_2_Act1_trajectories_soln" permid="Kmx">
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

        </li>

        <li permid="BYe">
          <p permid="QbJ">
            For <m>y(t) = 4 + 2e^{-t/2}</m>, we see that
            <me permid="tom">
              \frac{dy}{dt} = 2 \left( -\frac{1}{2} e^{-t/2} \right) = -e^{-t/2}
            </me>
            and
            <me permid="Zvv">
              -\frac{1}{2}( y - 4 ) = -\frac{1}{2} \left( 4 + 2e^{-t/2} \right) = -e^{-t/2}
            </me>
            In addition, <m>y(0) = 4 + 2e^0 = 6</m>.
            So <m>y(t) = 4 + 2e^{-t/2}</m> is a solution of the differential equation
            <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = -\frac{1}{2}(y - 4)</m> with <m>y(0) = 6</m>.
            The graph of this function is identical to the top graph in part (c).
          </p>
        </li>

        <li permid="ifn">
          <p permid="wiS">
            The solution where <m>y(0) = 4</m> is a constant function.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</activity>

